Linear regression can estimate non-linear relationship between variables.

set.seed(13371337)
x <- rnorm(1000, 0, 2)
y <- -x^2 + rnorm(length(x), 0, 1)
plot(y ~ x)

silly_mod <- lm(y ~ x)
summ(silly_mod)
Observations 1000
Dependent variable y
Type OLS linear regression
F(1,998) 1.21
R 0.00
Adj. R 0.00
Est. S.E. t val. p
(Intercept) -4.45 0.20 -22.20 0.00
x -0.10 0.10 -1.10 0.27
Standard errors: OLS 
plot(y ~ x)
abline(silly_mod, lwd = 2)

better_mod <- lm(y ~ x + I(x^2))
summ(better_mod)
Observations 1000
Dependent variable y
Type OLS linear regression
F(2,997) 21070.42
R 0.98
Adj. R 0.98
Est. S.E. t val. p
(Intercept) 0.00 0.04 0.04 0.97
x -0.01 0.01 -0.41 0.68
I(x^2) -1.00 0.00 -205.16 0.00
Standard errors: OLS 
effect_plot(better_mod, x, interval = TRUE, plot.points = TRUE)

Note, although nonparametric correlation approaches such as Kendalls \(\tau\) and siblings can deal with some nonlinear relationships, they only work for monotonic relationships. The one above isnt

cor_res <- cor.test(~ x + y, method = "kendall")
cor_res
## 
##  Kendall's rank correlation tau
## 
## data:  x and y
## z = 0.57485, p-value = 0.5654
## alternative hypothesis: true tau is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##        tau 
## 0.01214014

so the p-value is 0.57.
